line: [instrumental music plays]
[announcer] Ladies and gentlemen, please welcome to stage...
Simon Amstell.
[cheering and applause]
Hello.
[laughter]
I suppose the problem for humanity...
[laughter]
is there's a lot of people in here right now,
and everyone thinks that they're the special one,
even though all the evidence points towards the fact
that it is me.
[laughter]
I don't know why we need to feel so special as human beings.
We grasp for anything that will make us feel special.
I was dumped many years ago by somebody who went on to write an album.
I listened to the album thinking,
"I imagine a couple of these songs will be about me."
None of them.
[laughter]
The worst moment for me was seeing a picture of him online
being hugged by somebody who had also rejected me.
[laughter]
I sat there alone, thinking,
"I don't think there's any way that one of them is saying,
'How's Simon?'"
[laughter]
The therapist I saw for two years thought I needed to be so special
because I was terrified of intimacy.
In our first session, I was being quite funny,
and she said so wisely, "It's really good that you can be funny,
but, you know, you don't have to be funny here."
And I got what she was saying. I carried on talking.
And then she said,
"You know, you don't have to be interesting."
And then I was really confused and said,
"Do you want me to tell these stories but not as well?"
[laughter]
And what she wanted was for me to be authentic and grounded,
but I found that very difficult, because I'm so funny and interesting.
[laughter]
What I had to learn eventually was
it doesn't really matter how funny or interesting you think you can be.
You still can't get everyone to love you.
My dad, for example...
didn't come to the last couple of stand-up tours that I did,
and when I asked him why,
he said, "Well, I don't think you need my validation anymore, do you?"
And then he said that it wasn't his sort of thing.
[laughter]
And I wasn't brave enough to ask, "What? Comedy or me?"
[laughter]
For fear that he would say,
"Oh, no, I love comedy."
[laughter]
I realized in the end that my problem with my father is not my father.
It's my expectation of him as a father.
I thought, "Let's stop thinking of him as that
and just start thinking of him as a man who ejaculated."
[laughter]
Because often when men have ejaculated, they're tired.
You can't expect them to go on and love you.
[laughter]
I can't just keep screaming in my head for the rest of my life,
"If you can't love a child, don't ejaculate in a person.
Do it out of the window."
[laughter]
If I'm to focus on anything,
it should be on how grateful I am to my mom
for birthing me out of her body.
How can I ever thank her for that?
The best I can do is occasionally introduce her to a celebrity,
but is that enough?
[laughter]
"Thank you for your womb. Here's James Corden."
[laughter]
Not that my mom is perfect.
I had a memory of her screaming at my siblings and I one morning,
"One day, you'll come home from school and I'll be gone."
I reminded her of this, and she didn't remember,
but she said, "Look, I was a single parent."
And I said, "That's worse. One had already gone."
[laughter]
In a moment of openness on the phone recently with my mom,
she told me that when she was pregnant with me,
my dad wasn't being that great,
and a friend of hers called Mark took her out one day,
and he was so sweet and kind, she thought about leaving my father
and raising me with Mark instead.
She said, "Of course, I didn't do that, but that's why your middle name is Mark."
[laughter]
It's... it's very important not to talk to your parents.
[laughter]
But what are these problems? Are these problems?
I saw another therapist a while ago, and I was saying,
"Like, you know, compared to other people, what... what is any of this?"
And he said, "All feelings are valid."
He said, "If you lost a leg, and the person next door lost two legs,
you will still have lost a leg."
And I thought, "What is going on on this street?"
[laughter]
I think there have been problems. I think there have been problems.
I had a mild eating disorder a few years ago.
I don't know if it's an eating disorder.
I've never deliberately thrown up food,
but I have tried a bit too hard to poo. Now...
[laughter]
Is that... Is it an eating disorder
if once, to try and get something going, you poked a finger in? Is that...
[laughter]
It's not what you call classic bulimia, but it's something.
[laughter]
I don't know if that bit was worth the truth. I don't know.
[laughter]
So I hadn't seen my dad for a while,
and then I met up with him.
And his big news was he had trained to become a hypnotherapist,
which really angered me,
because I thought, "You can't be the therapist.
You're the trauma."
[laughter]
He then said that what would be great
is if I could introduce him to some of my crazy friends
so he could be a hypnotherapist to the stars.
I kept it all inside, because I thought, "Why express how I'm feeling to you now
when I can save it all up for a show that won't be your sort of thing?"
[laughter]
However, through this hypnotherapy training,
he developed a kind of emotional language that I hadn't witnessed in him before,
and we started talking about his very cold, distant mother.
And as he told me about her, I thought, "Oh, my God!
You are the more vulnerable one. You had the worst childhood.
I have to find some way to love you.
How did you turn it around, you sneaky, little hypnotist?"
[laughter]
I think maybe because of all that stuff,
I found it very difficult, or at least it took me a long time,
to become comfortable with the idea of being loved.
I just wasn't used intimacy, I suppose.
And then, when my boyfriend told me that he loved me,
it was a bit like what happened
when my brother cleaned his hamster's cage.
He'd never done that before,
and then when he cleaned the cage, the hamster died of shock.
[laughter]
Near the beginning of the relationship, we were in France together.
And it's really the most beautiful, authentic relationship I've ever been in.
And there were croissants.
[laughter]
And I think it's so good
because there is this real honesty between us.
We will talk about people who we find attractive.
That's so different to relationships I've been in in the past
where there was so much jealousy.
I was with someone for a while who was so jealous
I found myself having to say, "I really don't find anyone attractive.
[laughter]
And it's weird, because before I met you...
But they must have all moved."
[laughter]
In this relationship, we'll talk about people we find attractive.
We used to be a bit more sneaky about it.
Like, we'd go to see some ballet,
and we'd talk about the magic of the movements,
but we... we knew that what we were saying was,
"It'd be nice to take one home and lick him."
[laughter]
And we should be able to do that because the tickets are so expensive.
[laughter]
So, we were in France together,
and despite this being a near-perfect relationship,
or maybe because it's so perfect,
I fall asleep next to him,
and I have a dream that I'm in a sex dungeon
being seduced by--
I don't even know how to describe him other than "wet slut."
-I don't know. -[laughter]
And it wasn't water. It was lubricant.
He... he was just covered. [laughs]
[laughter]
He was covered in lubricant.
I should have known it was a dream, but my dreams aren't always this exciting.
The other night, I had a dream that I was in a queue.
[laughter]
And before I got to the end of the queue, I woke up.
[laughter]
So I said to this guy in the dungeon,
"It's lovely you've brought me here, but I'm in a relationship.
I can't really get involved."
And then I couldn't stop him, I think because he was so slippery.
[laughter]
And we did all kinds of sordid, wonderful things together.
But then, I thought, "Oh, my God! What have I done?
I've betrayed the best relationship I've ever been in.
What am I going to do? I've ruined my life."
And then I woke up.
I was in France. Everything was fine.
Everything was fine.
But then, for the next three days, all I could think was,
"I really loved that sex dungeon.
[laughter]
And is that who I really am?"
Because you can't argue with the unconscious.
Everything now just seems so appropriate and polite in real life.
"Do you want another croissant, Simon?"
"No, I want to shove this pain au chocolat up your ass."
[laughter]
"Your body's so dry."
[laughter]
I couldn't stop thinking that I was just this animal
who wanted to be in a dungeon,
and everything else is just a bit of conventional behavior.
And then...
I attended my boyfriend's mother's birthday dinner
where his brother gave this beautiful, heartfelt speech
about how much he loves his parents
and how he really appreciates
how accepting they've been of all their children
no matter who they turned out to be.
And I start crying,
feeling so safe and accepted here.
And I turned to my boyfriend, and I say,
"This is better than a sex dungeon."
[laughter]
The family found it very sweet, too.
[laughter]
And then, a couple of years into the relationship,
I met this very beautiful man
who seemed very interested in something happening between us that night,
and it seemed... it was just too...
it was too much,
but I walked away, because my relationship is my priority.
And it was... You know, I felt good, 'cause I was able to walk away,
but I couldn't stop thinking about what a shame it was
to not have been able to go with this moment,
and I felt really disgusting even thinking about it,
and I didn't want to bring it up with my boyfriend, but I eventually did.
And he looked very serious and then said, "I'm really glad you told me about that.
I guess what you're saying is you're a human being."
I said, "Oh, right. Yeah,
but I couldn't have slept with him, right?"
[laughter]
[laughter]
He said, "No, but I agree. It is a shame."
[laughter]
So we thought about it for a few days, discussed it, and came to the conclusion
we didn't really want to be in an open relationship,
but if somebody insanely beautiful just presented themselves to you,
maybe it would be silly not to go with it.
So, the rule is we don't sleep with people outside of the relationship,
but we could in principle
if it was unmissable and required no effort.
[laughter]
And because of that kind of communication,
last year, we were able to attend a sex party.
Thank you.
[laughter]
It would not have been possible for me before to go to a sex party.
I would've thought with my personality, what I bring to a social setting is humor,
and nobody wants an ironic blowjob.
[laughter]
"How was the orgy?" "Oh, so witty, so witty!"
[laughter]
But on this occasion, we both thought, "Oh, we're all going to die.
We must go to the sex party."
So, that's a phrase, isn't it? I think that's a phrase.
[laughter]
So, we were both a bit nervous, but we put it in our diaries, and then...
[laughter]
And then, one week before that sex party,
we were at a club night
where one of the floors suddenly just turned into a sex party.
And it was a week too soon.
[laughter]
We'd eaten pasta.
[laughter]
And we haven't discussed how involved we were going to get.
So we thought, "We'll just stay together
and do some very cautious touching of other bodies."
I touched a bottom that was so hard, it was like a cupboard.
[laughter]
And it was fun. But as someone who has often said things like,
"We're all just animals.
Why aren't we all naked and having sex all the time?"
Once everyone was naked and having sex,
I really wanted to see somebody in a hat.
[laughter]
Having thought for many years, "Why aren't we an orgy?
This should be an orgy. I want to be at an orgy."
At the end of that night, I thought, "Oh, God! Next we've got anther orgy."
[laughter]
But I feel so relieved, really,
more than grateful,
that I'm in this relationship where we can talk to each other.
We get to invent our lives together rather than...
I don't know, just sort of following
what other people think we should be doing.
I occasionally feel really threatened by normality.
I was at quite a traditional wedding recently and...
had a very strong feeling
that if the Nazis came to take me away,
the people at the wedding would feel sad,
but not stop them.
[laughter]
I felt quite angry all day.
[laughter]
I think, partly, I just can't believe people are still getting married.
People with degrees. What's going on?
[laughter]
They've already lived together for ten years.
Now they have to announce they're going to carry on as they are.
Why do I have to go to Dorset for that?
[laughter]
Have to announce you're so happy.
If you're so happy, stay in your house and shush.
[laughter]
Just send an email saying, "It's going very well. Carry on."
[laughter]
What would be wrong with this conversation?
"I love you." "I love you, too."
"Should we have a big event where we tell everyone we know?"
"Seem arrogant."
[laughter]
It's so smug. You wouldn't get everyone you know together to say,
"We made so much money. We think it will last until death."
[laughter]
With a bit at the end where you toss a bouquet of spare cash
at the poor people.
[laughter]
Don't like normality.
I felt really good visiting a school recently
that teaches children who are autistic.
And I ended up saying to the head teacher, "I don't really know anything,
but it feels like the child who is autistic doesn't have autism.
What they have is a kind of freedom
from all the nonsense that we have to accept as normal.
And if there's any stress or anxiety that they feel,
isn't that often from us,
trying to make them the same as everyone else?"
And she said, "Well, that's a nice idea.
[laughter]
But sometimes, they want to masturbate in public."
[laughter]
I nodded, but I thought, "So?"
[laughter]
Would it be so bad?
Like, isn't it worse for the parent in that moment
to shame the child, and feel ashamed, and everyone's so ashamed?
Better in that moment for the parent to say,
"People of the supermarket, gather."
[laughter]
I felt so conventional at this school.
I went to shake this kid's hand, and as I was shaking his hand,
I could see him thinking, "This is bullshit, isn't it?"
[laughter]
It was interesting to see what had to be taught.
I was in a class of kids being taught to spread jam on toast.
It's not that they can't do that.
You can just see them thinking, "Why... [stammers]
This is just wasting valuable masturbation time."
[laughter]
I think the world doesn't make enough sense
for everyone to be expected to fit in to it.
In this country,
we have a royal family,
and not just in the past.
Now.
[laughter]
People are very interested in them.
To me, the only thing that's really interesting about them is
they don't seem to be embarrassed.
[laughter]
They walk into rooms. There are trumpets.
[laughter]
If that was me, at some point, I would have to say,
"Please, you mustn't. It's ridiculous.
[laughter]
I'm just you. I'm basically you." But that's not what they do.
They stand there, and they must be thinking,
"Yes, this is appropriate.
[laughter]
I was born."
[laughter]
I worry for them sometimes.
There must be so much denial in their lives.
Imagine every morning, you wake up, you do a shit,
and then for the rest of the day, you have to pretend that it didn't happen.
[laughter]
Because if you're just a person who does a shit,
the trumpets are gonna start to sound sarcastic.
[laughter]
Because no one is special.
It doesn't matter what you do or even what you achieve.
The ending is the same.
You win the Olympics. You die.
You get your dream home. You die.
You're pregnant. Oh, you both die.
[laughter]
No one is special.
Certainly, not in a major city like London.
Like, it's not even that exciting to you people that I'm here.
[laughter]
And I'm very famous.
[laughter]
People in the middle of England would lose their minds.
[laughter]
We're all basically the same thing, and yet everything is about status.
On every chat show on TV, it's, "Welcome to the show.
Here's another famous person who's done another amazing thing."
And it's unsettling for all of us.
Really, it should be, "Welcome to the show.
As you know, life is suffering, and the self is an illusion.
[laughter]
Please welcome my next guest,
whose face is a mask covering an unknowable void."
[laughter]
Nobody feels happy where they are.
I decided a few years ago that it was very important,
important,
that I go to America and start being funny there.
And only 'cause I thought it would be a bit embarrassing if I don't.
Like, "Who am I if I don't go to America?
Some regional comedian...
[laughter]
who's a bit famous on one tiny island,
and if I go anywhere else, I'm...
I'm you."
[laughter]
So, I went to New York City,
and I did these shows. It went really well.
It should have been pure joy.
Everything in my head became about, "What can I achieve?
Where will I get to?"
And finally, somebody said to me,
"Simon, you're doing these shows in New York. People--
Everyone's coming to see you. They're laughing.
If you're not happy now, you'll never be happy."
And I thought, "Oh...
I'll never be happy."
[laughter]
It's not like you even get what you used to get in show business,
which was this feeling of elevation,
of definitely being special.
Before one of those shows in New York,
somebody sent me a message over Twitter,
which said, "Can you let us know what time the show finishes?
We have to book a babysitter."
[laughter]
I'm the star.
[laughter]
You can't just talk to me.
[laughter]
I felt completely lost in LA.
But then I met this guru,
It turned out he wasn't really a guru, but he had very good posture, and...
[laughter]
And I was very drawn to his charisma,
and I thought, "He seems at peace. Maybe if I can listen to him,
if I listen to everything he says, I'll have peace in my life, finally."
And we were talking about meditation one day.
I said I'd begun to enjoy meditation.
Just feels like something I'm doing now every day.
Not like a duty, you know?
And he said, "Well, do you know what that is?"
I said, "What you mean?"
He said, "You've gone from discipline...
to blissipline."
[laughter]
I thought I was gonna be happy.
[laughter]
I went to see this dance piece.
[laughter]
Don't go and see something if it's a piece.
[laughter]
If somebody says to you,
"Would you like to come and see my piece?"
[laughter]
You have to say, "Oh, I'm so sorry.
I've hurt one of my fingers.
[laughter]
I'd love to see the piece.
Maybe let me know when it's the whole thing."
[laughter]
It was this solo dancer...
I'm gonna go down again.
[laughter]
...rolling around on a floor,
and then, at one point, she pulled a giant sheet of paper over her head.
I guess to give the feeling...
Where is she?
[laughter]
And then, as the music climaxed,
her foot burst through the paper.
And nobody laughed.
[laughter]
I think the problem is we don't die quick enough.
[laughter]
Somebody said to me the other day, "You know, in 40 years, you'll be 79."
And I thought, "How long is this gonna go on for?"
[laughter]
We just keep living,
so you have to keep coming up with things to do.
That's why you're here, so you've done something tonight.
[laughter]
'Cause tomorrow, people will say, "What did you do last night?
You'll say, "I went to this comedy show 'cause I live in London. I'm alive."
[laughter]
Are you, though?
[laughter]
Or are you just desperately filling the time
so you don't have to feel any pain?
[laughter]
Well, you came to the wrong show.
[laughter]
It's not that I'm even depressed anymore. I just don't know what this is.
It used to be that I almost couldn't get out of bed in the morning.
Now, I get out of bed, but I don't know why I've done it.
[laughter]
I'm so annoyed I still have to earn money.
I do know how you feel.
[laughter]
I feel like we were children playing,
and then, suddenly, this economic system where nothing is ever enough,
causing endless anxiety, destroying the planet.
I said to my agent, "Is there any way out of this?
Could I be a not-for-profit comedian?"
And she said, "You're getting there."
[laughter]
And so, feeling completely lost,
desperate to figure out who I'm supposed to be in this world,
I ended up...
in a sweat lodge.
A sweat lodge, if you don't know, is a Native American ritual
for resolving inner or outer conflict in a hot, womb-like teepee in Norfolk.
[laughter]
There were two sweat lodge ceremonies.
In the first one,
I found that I was just a bit too embarrassed to get involved,
because it was so powerful and sincere.
People were forgiving their parents and honoring them.
It was too much.
But in the second ceremony,
I thought, "Come on, you know. Life is very short...
as well as much too long.
[laughter]
Be in the teepee,"
and a conflict of gender equality arose.
The shaman had explained the women who were on their moon period,
which is what the shaman called a period...
[laughter]
were not allowed in the teepee at that time.
This caused a bit of tension,
in part because one of the women who was on her moon period
snuck in.
[laughter]
And the shaman, I guess from his decades of training, knew.
[laughter]
And as a response,
this shaman suddenly took on this sexist character,
kind of like a trickster, misogynist guy, to further inflame the tension.
And some of the women in the heat and the madness of it all started crying.
The men looked deeply troubled like they didn't know what to do.
And then my whole body started vibrating,
and I thought, "Maybe I alone hold the power to end misogyny."
[laughter]
Because the truth is how can there be any sexism? How...
I mean, we all come from a woman. When... when do we begin to be sexist?
Are we there in the womb, thinking, "Well, this is all very well,
but I think my dad would do a better job."
[laughter]
Can you imagine emerging
from this life-giving, warm, nurturing place
and then going, "Okay. Thank you.
Set fire to that now."
[laughter]
How can the worst thing you can call someone be cunt?
This is where we all emerge from.
To say to someone, "You're a cunt," is to say, "You're the doorway to life."
[laughter]
It's like calling somebody an asshole.
If we didn't have assholes, we'd explode.
[laughter]
To say to someone, "You're an asshole,"
is to say, "You're a vital member of this community."
[laughter]
Maybe... maybe some of the misogyny
comes from the fact that we were ejected from the womb.
We weren't allowed to stay there.
And then maybe we were breastfed, but then, that had to be stopped as well.
We definitely miss our mothers' breast milk.
Of course we do.
Of course we do.
[laughter]
Otherwise, why would we have started stealing milk from other species?
[laughter]
The cows must be thinking,
"This has nothing to do with you.
[laughter]
This is for my child.
[laughter]
It's... it's not for your Coco Pops.
[laughter]
You think this... Maybe this is an issue with your mother?"
[laughter]
Can you imagine if calves started attaching themselves to human women...
[laughter]
and then complaining of lactose intolerance?
[laughter]
And women, women...
women, you control the continuation of human existence.
Until there is equality, you could stop breeding.
Maybe it's not for me to tell you what to do with your bodies, but...
[laughter]
I suppose have a baby if you really wanna have a baby,
but if it's a boy, you must abort.
-Yes. -[laughter]
Yes, because it's a war.
If you're a woman having sex with a man and creating more men,
you should be hung for treason.
[laughter]
Do you think Winston Churchill would have got pregnant
if there was a 50/50 chance it could be a Nazi?
[laughter]
And so, in the intense heat of that teepee,
my soul transcended any embarrassment,
and I found myself saying,
"I would like to honor my mother
for doing her best under very difficult circumstances."
And then I found myself saying
that I would also like to honor my child self for doing the same.
Something shifted.
I felt strong, ready to be reborn.
But I wanted to do something to protect this child self
before he was thrust into the patriarchal madness
of suburban Essex, so...
[laughter]
I started covering myself in mud.
Nobody else was doing this.
[laughter]
I crawled out of that teepee.
I fell down to the grass. I burst into tears
in part for everything that lost child had gone through,
and in part because I knew that misogyny had ended forever.
[laughter]
I think I also realized in that teepee
that one of the major reasons I found intimacy so difficult is...
I had to pretend to be another person for about eight years.
I never wanted to talk about this like it was a big deal,
but think that maybe it's dishonoring the 13 year old
who had to cope with liking boys and not being able to tell anyone.
I was so terrified at 13 that I might like boys.
I remember thinking that it was probably the fear of liking boys
that was causing me to like boys.
This made sense to me at the time,
even though I know people who are scared of heights
don't also have an intense sexual urge to sit on a roof.
[laughter]
"Where are you going?"
[laughter]
"How funny do I have to be, Daddy?"
[laughter]
I didn't know what to do. I couldn't talk to anyone.
So, I decided at the age of 18, I would go to Paris on my own, in secret,
to figure out if I really did like boys or if it just was this fear in my head.
So, and I remember packing... I got on the train.
I'd packed a small, black t-shirt, contact lenses, and hair gel.
That was it.
'Cause I thought, "How will these French people resist...
a skinny boy with spiky hair and the suggestion of eyesight?"
[laughter]
As soon as I arrived in Paris,
I freaked out slightly that nobody knew I was there.
I thought, "My God! I could just die here, and nobody will get why.
They'll say, "All he had on him was hair gel. What was his plan?'"
[laughter]
I was so nervous walking into this nightclub.
I'd never been to a nightclub before.
And what I thought would happen...
This is quite naive maybe,
but thought that I was this new guy in town,
somebody, at least one person, would approach me and tell me who I am.
Nobody did that, no one.
And that's still so weird to me, because...
when I think about that lost, shy,
vulnerable, anxious young man,
I think,
"That's my type."
[laughter]
I wish I'd been there for me.
[laughter]
In therapy, we discussed why I was often drawn to younger men,
and it turned out I was trying to save the 18 year old in me who wasn't saved.
You may prefer to think of me as a pervert, but...
[laughter]
I'm actually a narcissist.
[laughter]
And a pervert.
[laughter]
So, I eventually just got drunk enough
so that I could go up to this very cute guy
and say the French for, "Will you kiss me?"
And he just shrugged and kissed me.
It was so amazing.
I still remember thinking as he was kissing me,
"Oh, yeah, gay."
[laughter]
It was amazing. It ended much too quickly, though.
He had to leave. I didn't have the French for,
"I'm only here for one night. Please stay."
I can't believe that my French wasn't better
when two years earlier, I'd received an A Star
on my GCSE oral exam for brilliant sentences like,
"Mon pre travaille dans la banque."
[laughter]
My dad didn't work in a bank,
but I didn't know how to say, "He runs a cab company,"
and I thought, "Who's gonna check?"
[laughter]
So I thought, "Well, maybe I know who I am now. I could just go home."
But I thought, "I've come all this way. It's a long way to come.
It's a shame not to touch a penis." So...
